2. Docker Fundamentals

Docker is a platform that packages:

Application code

Dependencies

Runtime

into a portable unit called a container.

Why Docker matters

Consistent environments across systems

Fast deployments

Lightweight compared to VMs

Ideal for microservices architecture

3. Docker CLI Basics
docker version

Displays Docker client and server versions.

docker help

Lists all available Docker commands.

docker ps

Shows running containers.

docker ps -a

Shows all containers (including stopped ones).

docker search <image>

Searches images in Docker Hub. Prefer official images.

4. Running Containers
docker run -it ubuntu

Runs an interactive Ubuntu container.

-i → interactive

-t → terminal

Detach from container without stopping it:

CTRL + P + Q
docker run -itd ubuntu:latest

Runs container in detached mode.

⚠️ Avoid using latest in production environments.

docker attach <container_id>

Attach to a running container.

Preferred method:

docker exec -it <container_id> bash
5. Container Lifecycle Management
docker start <id>
docker stop <id>

stop → graceful shutdown

kill → immediate termination

docker pause <id>

Pauses all processes inside the container.

docker unpause <id>

Resumes paused container.

docker run --rm ubuntu

Automatically removes container after it exits.

6. Naming and File Operations
docker run --name=mycontainer ubuntu

Assigns a name to a container.

docker cp <container_id>:/path/file .

Copies files between container and host.

7. Port Mapping
docker run -d -p 8080:80 nginx

8080 → host port

80 → container port

This maps external traffic to the container.

8. Images and Registry Operations
docker commit <container_id> myimage

Creates an image from a container (not recommended for production).

docker export <container_id> > container.tar

Exports container filesystem.

docker tag ubuntu myrepo/ubuntu:v1

Tags an image.

docker login

Authenticates with a container registry.

9. Docker Daemon
service docker status
service docker stop
service docker start

Modern systems:

systemctl status docker
10. Docker Networking
docker network ls

Lists networks.

docker run -it --network=bridge ubuntu
docker run -it --network=host ubuntu
docker run -it --network=none ubuntu
Network Types

Bridge

Default network (docker0)

Isolated container communication

Host

Uses host IP and ports

No isolation

None

No network interface

Key Concepts

Network Namespace → isolates network per container

Veth Pair → virtual link between container and host

Port Mapping → exposes container services

Low-level inspection:

ip netns
ip netns exec <ns> <command>
11. Docker Storage
/var/lib/docker

Stores:

Images

Containers

Volumes

Used for debugging disk and storage issues.

12. Docker Disk Usage
docker system df
docker system df -v

Displays disk usage details.

13. Docker Cleanup
docker system prune

Removes unused resources.

docker system prune -a

Removes:

Stopped containers

Unused images

Unused networks

⚠️ Use carefully in production.

14. Dockerfile (Production Standard)
FROM python:3.11-slim

WORKDIR /app

COPY requirements.txt .
RUN pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt

COPY . .

CMD ["python", "app.py"]
Best Practices

Use minimal base images

Reduce layers

Use caching effectively

Avoid unnecessary dependencies

15. Resource Management
docker run -m 512m --cpus=1 nginx

Prevents:

Memory overuse (OOMKilled)

CPU starvation

16. Logging
docker logs <container_id>

Best practices:

Use stdout/stderr

Do not store logs inside containers

Integrate with centralized logging systems

17. Security
docker run --user 1000 nginx

Best practices:

Avoid running as root

Use minimal images

Scan for vulnerabilities

Apply security profiles (seccomp, capabilities)

